ewish selfhood for centuries. Pushing us to reassess the boundaries between race and ethnicity, it offers insight into how Black Jewish individuals strive to assert their dual identities and find acceptance within their respective communities. Putting to rest the simplistic notion that Jews are white and that Black Jews are therefore a contradiction, the volume argues that we can no longer pigeonhole Black Hebrews and Israelites as exotic, militant, and nationalistic sects outside the boundaries of mainstream Jewish thought and community life. The volume spurs us to consider the significance of the growing population of self-identified Black Jews and its implications for the future of American Jewry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American JewsxHistory. 0aJewsxIdentity. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican-American Hebrew.  aAfro-American.  aAshkenazi Jews.  aBeta Israel.  aBlack Hebrew.  aBlack Hebrews.  aChristianity.  aConversos.  aEthiopian Hebrews.  aHutus and Tutsis.  aIsraelite communities.  aJewish diaspora.  aJewish identity.  aJewish intellectuals.  aJudaism.  aOrientalist thinking.  aSephardic.  aUS census.  aWhiteness.  aancient Israelites.  aanti-Semitism.  abiracial Jews.  ablack Jews.  ablack converts.  ablack-Jewish identities.  ablack-Jewish relations.  aconversion.  adouble consciousness.  aeastern European Jews.  aglobal Jewish narrative.  akinship.  apolitical orientation.  aracial consciousness.  aracial performance.  aracial project.  aracial projects.  aracial taxonomies.  aracialization.  aracism.  areligious practice.  asituational passing.  aslavery.  astrategic essentialism.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479887927.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978147988792742